translated: Englund, Josef Emanuel, lecturer, Jönköping, born on December 3, 1889 in Gävle to Lars E. and his wife, nee Lundberg. Married to Margareta Thedenius in 1917. They have one daughter named Rut, born in 1921. Englund graduated from high school in Gävle in 1909, received a Bachelor's degree from Uppsala University in 1912, a Master's degree in 1913, a Licentiate degree from the University of Gothenburg in 1932, and a Doctorate degree in 1937. He worked as a temporary assistant in Hudiksvall from 1914 to 1915, Skara in 1917, Gävle in 1917-1918, Kalmar in 1918-1919, temporary lecturer there in 1919-1920, temporary assistant in Uppsala in 1920-1921, and a permanent teacher there in 1921-1922. He was an assistant in Visby in 1922 and a lecturer in Latin and Greek at Jönköping from 1922 until his death in 1957. Englund traveled to Germany, Switzerland and France in 1927, and Italy in 1937. He wrote a dissertation on the medical writer Cornelius Celsus titled: "Celsus' description of ulcers" which was approved for a doctoral degree in 1935.
